text: By all means we should support <@U011VKB18NM> starting as soon as possible. As I have mentioned during the Zoom meeting, I will support not only taking care of the PCB layout design for them but also connecting <@U011VKB18NM> with Altium <https://www.altium.com/> so they will have access to the design tool. As long as the product is not going to be for profit and the project is on COVID-19 then they will work help us to have access to the tool. The Altium tool will cost any where from $6,000 for one license all the way to $10K. I will forward the email communication that I have with Altium to <@U010986778X> and then see how we can continue the communication. I have already mentioned to Altium about this group but their expectation is that we are going to work on the Medtronic open source release. But seeing what <@U011VKB18NM> is doing and has accomplished so far, I am sure they will be willing to keep their offer. The key is - it has to be on COVID-19 and it should not be to make profit.  As far as the Medtronic design I am determined to work on it and at least do what I can and have it available to any one who will take care of the Software and the Mechanical design. But even to do that I need support from an Electrical Engineer who can look into the schematic and make sure that we can own it as it is. There is already a group in the states who are working on it as open source and I am part of it. But I was hoping that we (Ethiopians) will have control over it and use it 1. to have it manufactured in Ethiopia (of course not all of the needed components will be available in Ethiopia) but we will be able to design the main parts and have full control over it. We can also think of it as a complete knock down (CKD) assembly but we have to start from either getting and or making some of the parts.  2. We will be able to use it to transfer knowledge among each other and especially to our brothers and sisters in Ethiopia. Other well know manufactures are going to be doing the same exact thing. Of course they have all the resources and they can easily access the materials. But as they say ከልብ ካለቀሱ እንባ አይገድም. I am not even going to try and translate it to English :slightly_smiling_face: 3. I hope, trust and pray that COVID-19 will not affect our Ethiopia as much as it did in the rest of the world, but God forbid and if it does, then the effect is going to stay for a while so having this project started and working on it as soon as possible will only help us in the near future. Either way please let me know how to proceed and how I can help.

text:
I hope everyone is having a good weekend! 

<@U011VKB18NM> please upload any files you’d like the team to look at : <https://drive.google.com/open?id=1QiY1fOoSio3neLQevubhwuwMdwptuatg>

In the meantime, I think we can get started with defining our design inputs/product specification by defining the minimum performance criteria, requirements, and features for a mechanical ventilator. 

Any thoughts on this approach? Let me know if you are available to work on this.

For more info on the plan, please see <https://drive.google.com/file/d/1N11eM-eSMTVBoThiBejkZj6Cq7aWwAUy/view?usp=sharing>

I am also working on updating this plan and formulating a regulatory strategy for approval based on the temporary medical product approval and import permit authorization directive from Ethiopia and, FDA EUA that’s been shared in this channel.
